ces within Yoruba culture have enabled women to contest the full acceptance of those new norms. Oyeronke Olademo asserts that Yoruba women attain and wield agency in family and society through their economic and religious roles, and Yoruba operate within a system of gender balance, so that neither of the sexes can be subsumed in the other. Olademo utilizes historical and phenomenological methods, incorporating impressive data from interviews and participant-observation, showing how religion is at the core of Yoruba lived experiences and is intricately bound up in all sectors of daily life in Yorubaland and abroad in the diaspora.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aWomen and religion. 0aWomen, YorubaxReligion. 0aYoruba (African people)xReligion. 7aRELIGION / Ethnic & Tribal.2bisacsh  aAfrican Independent Churches.  aAmirah.  aCandomblé.  aChristianity in Yorubaland.  aGẹ̀lẹ̀dẹ, Gelede.  aHaitian Vodou.  aLGBTQ persons and Yoruba religion in the diaspora.  aMission Churches.  aMuallimaat.  aPentecostal churches.  aQur’an and women’s roles in Islam.  aSantería.  aWomen in Yoruba religion.  aYoruba constructions of gender.  aYoruba gender relations.  aYoruba religion and globalization.  aYoruba religion in the diaspora.  aYoruba women and commercialization of religion.  aYoruba women and globalization.  aYoruba women and religious global networking.  aYoruba women and social media and internet.  aYoruba women in Christianity and Islam in the diaspora.  aYoruba women in socio-economic life.  aYoruba women’s Christian prayer group.  aYoruba women’s Islamic prayer groups.  aYoruba women’s leadership in Islam.  aYoruba women’s leadership.  aYoruba women’s religious leadership.  aYoruba women’s roles in churches.  aYoruba women’s spiritual power.  aYorubaland. 